    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIf an argument is optional, the error message produced by `vim.validate` does not reflect this in cases where argument does not satisfy a validator.\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/5d85669a33e10f1f156b086562458cbbc8054438/runtime/lua/vim/_core/shared.lua#L1114-L1172\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `:lua vim.validate('arg_name', 123, 'string', true)`\n2. BUG: The error message states that a `string` was expected, whereas `nil` is also acceptable\n```\nE5108: Lua: [string \":lua\"]:1: arg_name: expected string, got number\nstack traceback:\n\t[C]: in function 'error'\n\tvim/_core/shared.lua: in function 'validate'\n\t[string \":lua\"]:1: in main chunk\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIn the STR above, the message should've mentioned that either a `string` or a `nil` was expected. Although I'm not sure what the exact wording should be.\n\nMy proposal is:\n1. If `{message}` is specified, print `expected <MESSAGE> or nil, got <ACTUAL TYPE>`\n2. If `{validator}` is a string, print `expected <VALIDATOR>|nil, got <ACTUAL TYPE>`\n3. If `{validator}` is an array of strings, print `expected <TYPE1>|<TYPE2>|<..>|nil, got <ACTUAL TYPE>`. If `nil` is already in the array, don't print it twice\n4. If `{validator}` is a function, print `expected ? or nil, got <ACTUAL TYPE>` (currently it prints `expected ?, got <ACTUAL TYPE>`)\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.2\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nvim doesn't have lua api\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nany\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nany\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nany\n\n### Installation\n\nany",
